o","body":"Julia Ann Hooker married Frederick William Hopkins — who served as Adjutant and Inspector General of Vermont and compiled the state's military laws — in December 1836, the same year her brother John moved to Chicago. She died in Chicago September 27, 1842, one of two Thomas Hooker children to die in that city."},{"number":2,"category":"family","header":"Died at thirty-three; daughter Sarah Hooker survived her","body":"Julia Ann died in Chicago at about thirty-three in 1842, leaving a daughter Sarah Hooker Hopkins — whose middle name Hooker honored the family line — who was just five years old. Her husband Frederick survived her and continued his Vermont legal career."}],"naming_inspiration":[],"quotes":[],"documents":[],"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM553","plot_notes":"West Street Cemetery, Rutland VT. FGA #. She died in Chicago but was buried in the family cemetery in Rutland."},"residence":{"country":"United States"},"sources":[{"short":"EH 1909 #1420"}],"research_sources":[],"slug":"julia-hooker-1810"},"I01192":{"id":"I01192","is_placeholder":false,"has_descendants_documented":false,"former_ids":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Frederic Williams Hopkins","first_name":"Frederic","middle_name":"Williams","last_name":"Hopkins","married_names":[],"photo_url":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dc5clrqtw/image/upload/v1779484860/frederichopkins_xsjrwk.jpg","photo_notes":"Portrait. Cloudinary collection via Sam."},"gender":"male","birth":{"year":1806,"month":9,"day":15,"city":"Pittsford","county":"Rutland","state":"Vermont","country":"United States"},"death":{"year":1874,"month":1,"day":21,"city":"Rutland","county":"Rutland","state":"Vermont"},"baptism":{},"classification":{"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_thomas_spouse":true,"is_talcott_spouse":false,"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"is_progenitor":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"parents":{},"notable":{"is_notable":true,"notable_category":["military","law"],"notable_blurb":"Vermont lawyer and militia officer","primary_url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frederic_Williams_Hopkins","primary_url_label":"Wikipedia — Frederic Williams Hopkins"},"number_of_marriages":1,"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"H01420","date_year":1836,"end_type":"death_of_spouse","end_year":1842,"children_ids":["H02773","H02774"]}],"career":[{"role":"Justice of the Peace","location":"Rutland, Vermont","notes":"Long-time Rutland Justice of the Peace."},{"role":"Register of Probate","organization":"Rutland County","location":"Rutland, Vermont","start_year":1832,"end_year":1839,"notes":"1832-1836 and 1838-1839."},{"role":"Adjutant and Inspector General","organization":"Vermont Militia","location":"Vermont","start_year":1837,"end_year":1852,"notes":"Vermont Adjutant and Inspector General 1837-1852. Worked with Franklin Pierce, Alden Partridge, Truman B. Ransom in militia reform."},{"role":"Clerk of Courts","organization":"Rutland County Courts","location":"Rutland, Vermont","start_year":1839,"end_year":1868,"notes":"Earned accolades leaving sick bed to save court records during courthouse fire April 3, 1868."},{"role":"Organizer","organization":"Rutland Union School District","location":"Rutland, Vermont","start_year":1855,"notes":"Organized Rutland Union School District 1855. Also organized Rutland's first volunteer fire department."}],"education":[{"school_name":"Middlebury College","dates":"graduated 1828","type":"undergraduate","notes":"Graduated Middlebury College 1828 per Wikipedia."}],"military_service":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"tags":["lawyer","politician"],"research_tags":[],"cross_connections":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"career","header":"Compiled Vermont's military laws; state adjutant general","body":"Frederic Williams Hopkins graduated Middlebury College, practiced law as clerk of Rutland County Court, and rose to Adjutant and Inspector General of the State of Vermont, compiling the state's military laws. He married Julia Ann Hooker in December 1836, the same month her brother John moved to Chicago."},{"category":"law","header":"He clerked the county courts for years","body":"A Middlebury graduate, Hopkins practiced law at Rutland and long served as clerk of the Rutland County courts. His grave was vandalized in 1891 and his remains moved to Evergreen Cemetery.","number":2}],"naming_inspiration":[],"quotes":[],"documents":[],"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM554","plot_notes":"Originally buried West Street Cemetery CEM553; remains moved to Evergreen Cemetery after 1891 grave vandalism."},"residence":{"country":"United States"},"sources":[{"short":"EH 1909 #1420"},{"short":"Wikipedia — Frederic Williams Hopkins","page":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frederic_Williams_Hopkins"}],"research_sources":[],"slug":"frederic-hopkins-1806"},"H00530":{"id":"H00530","has_descendants_documented":true,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"generation_from_thomas":6,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"birth":{"year":1770,"month":5,"day":20,"city":"Northampton","state":"Massachusetts","county":"Hampshire"},"death":{"year":1836,"month":4,"day":14,"city":"Rutland","county":"Rutland","state":"Vermont"},"parents":{"father_id":"H00264","mother_id":"I00043"},"tags":["merchant","vermont_migration"],"sources":[{"short":"Edward Hooker 1909","page":"Entry 530"}],"gender":"male","marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"I01188","date_year":1796,"end_type":"death_of_spouse","end_year":1832,"children_ids":["H01416","H01417","H01418","H01419","H01420"]}],"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Thomas Hooker","first_name":"Thomas","last_name":"Hooker","married_names":[]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM553"},"career":[{"role":"Apothecary and Grocer","location":"Rutland, Rutland County, Vermont","end_year":1836,"notes":"Per EH 1909 #530: 'an apothecary and grocer at Rutland, Vt.'"}],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"career","header":"Apothecary and grocer at Rutland; wife predeceased him","body":"Thomas Hooker was an apothecary and grocer at Rutland, Vermont, where he spent his adult life and died in 1836 at sixty-five. His wife Sarah Brown died four years before him in 1832, predeceasing him despite being nine years younger."},{"number":2,"category":"marriage","header":"Married daughter of Col. John Brown of Pittsfield","body":"Sarah Brown's father, Colonel John Brown of Pittsfield, Massachusetts, is almost certainly the Revolutionary War officer killed at the Battle of Stone Arabia, New York, on October 19, 1780 — when Sarah was barely a year old. If confirmed, Thomas Hooker married the daughter of a Revolutionary War martyr."},{"number":3,"category":"family","header":"Twin sons: one to Boston missions","body":"John Worthington and Henry Brown Hooker were born the same day — August 31, 1802 — and their lives diverged completely: John moved to Chicago in 1836 among the city's earliest New England settlers, while Henry graduated Middlebury College, entered the ministry, and became Secretary of Missions at Boston."},{"number":4,"category":"family","header":"Two of five children died in Chicago","body":"John Worthington Hooker moved to Chicago in 1836 and died there in 1866; his sister Julia Ann married a Rutland lawyer and also died in Chicago in 1842. Two of Thomas Hooker's five children ended their days in the city that barely existed when they were born."}],"number_of_marriages":1,"slug":"thomas-hooker-1770"},"I01188":{"id":"I01188","is_placeholder":false,"has_descendants_documented":false,"former_ids":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Sarah Brown Hooker","first_name":"Sa